<HEADLINE>
<P>
VIETNAM ASKED TO CURB EXODUS OF 'BOAT PEOPLE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Delegates from 30 nations have drafted a plan asking Vietnam to curtail the 
exodus of "boat people" from its shores, officials at an international 
conference said. 
</P>
<P>
However, the group, which held a three-day meeting here this week, ruled out 
forcibly repatriating asylum-seekers who cannot show they are fleeing political 
persecution, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
"The rules are very clear . . . whenever refugees are repatriated, it has to be 
on a voluntary basis," said Jean Pierre Hocke, the U.N. high commissioner for 
refugees. 
</P>
<P>
The delegates laid out the measures in a draft plan for consideration at the 
International Conference on Indochinese Refugees, to be held June 13-14 in 
Geneva. 
</P>
<P>
Chairman Majid Mohammed said that the plan would help "provide durable 
solutions to the Indochinese refugee problem." 
</P>
<P>
The draft plan suggests that Vietnam launch a campaign stressing the risks and 
hardships of fleeing by boat and work to end illegal departures by "boat 
people." It also calls on Vietnam to make legal departures easier. 
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand, the Philippines and other countries in the 
region have agreed to provide temporary asylum for refugees. Western nations 
were urged to take in refugees left in camps. 
</P>
<P>
The officials said the Vietnamese delegation had agreed at the conference to 
take back anyone who wants to return voluntarily. 
</P>
<P>
Western delegations said they might take in additional refugees and step up 
financial aid to help implement the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
