<HEADLINE>
<P>
TRUCKER RECEIVES 4-YEAR TERM FOR FREEWAY RAMPAGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By EDWIN CHEN, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Charley Tom Lee Jr. was a man who always kept a tight lid on his emotions, his 
family members told the judge. In all of 25 years, he never raised his voice in 
anger. Not even once, they said. 
</P>
<P>
That is, until May 18, when 21 Los Angeles motorists discovered just how 
violent the truck driver from Texas could be when he finally blew his top. 
</P>
<P>
For that outburst, a contrite Lee was sentenced to four years in state prison 
Friday by Los Angeles Superior Court Judge Judith Chirlin despite impassioned 
pleas for probation by Lee's wife, mother, grandmother and defense lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
On that May afternoon, Lee began rear-ending cars with his 18-wheel semi at 
speeds up to 80 m.p.h., starting on the San Bernardino Freeway in Temple City, 
and continuing on until California Highway Patrol officers finally pulled him 
over at gunpoint on the Hollywood Freeway in Los Angeles, leaving a 35-mile 
trail of leaking fuel, broken glass and twisted scraps of metal. 
</P>
<P>
His family said he had been under tremendous pressure on the day of the 
incident. He was distraught over his mother's chronic illness. He was beside 
himself over his father's attempted suicide. He was upset because he could not 
provide a better life for his bride and infant daughter. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Truck Broke Down 
</P>
<P>
In addition, on the day of the rampage, Lee's truck had broken down, he had 
lost the keys to the tractor-trailer, and he had had an unpleasant encounter 
with a waitress somewhere along the way, they said. 
</P>
<P>
Lee did not speak in court Friday. But in a letter to Chirlin, he apologized to 
his victims and said he still has no explanation for his "erratic behavior" 
that afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
Lee in November pleaded guilty to five counts of assault with a deadly weapon 
in exchange for the dismissal of 11 other felony counts, including possession 
of a loaded handgun and a small amount of amphetamines. 
</P>
<P>
He faced up to eight years in prison, although a county probation report 
recommended supervised probation. 
</P>
<P>
According to Los Angeles Deputy Dist. Atty. Craig Veals, Lee could be released 
in about a year, considering the time Lee has already served in County Jail. 
</P>
<P>
In sentencing Lee, Chirlin said she could not ignore the nature of his crime. 
She said she has received numerous calls "from a variety of people" with 
strongly held opinions that were "split down the middle." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
'Living Out Fantasies' 
</P>
<P>
Some told the judge that Lee was "living out their fantasies" while others said 
what Lee had done was "every driver's nightmare." 
</P>
<P>
Lee's family members testified -- often tearfully -- that they had "never" seen 
him angry. Always, said his mother, Billie Lee, he would "walk away" from 
unpleasant situations. 
</P>
<P>
For instance, when she told him that his father had attempted suicide, she 
said, Lee just ran and ran until he finally dropped in exhaustion. "He blamed 
himself," she said. 
</P>
<P>
After the freeway rampage, Lee told her "it was like a bad dream," Billie Lee 
said. 
</P>
<P>
"I never saw him angry," added Lee's grandmother, Dorothy Lee. She said he 
always had a sweet disposition -- from infancy, when she used to keep him in a 
potato bin in her grocery store in Missouri. She called him "Tater." 
</P>
<P>
Tammy Lee, his wife, said she had accompanied her husband on many cross-country 
trips and never once saw him "get violent" on the road. He was "a very 
courteous" driver, she said. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Concerns Over Money 
</P>
<P>
On the road, they almost always slept in the truck to save money, she said, 
adding that he had become increasingly upset at not being able to provide a 
better life for his family. 
</P>
<P>
"He didn't think he was doing enough for me and Chastity (their now 
19-month-old daughter)," she said. "It really upset him." 
</P>
<P>
Laura Green, the Los Angeles deputy public defender who represented Lee, asked 
Chirlin to grant Lee probation, noting that her client has relatives in 
California, in Nevada and in Missouri who are willing to look after him. 
</P>
<P>
But Chirlin, noting that this was "an extremely difficult case," said she could 
not overlook his crimes. And Veals said it was "sheer happenstance" that no one 
had been seriously injured in the rampage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
